issue.title: Create comprehensive migration strategy for mixin fields (#195)
issue.body:
## Summary

Implements a comprehensive migration strategy for safely applying mixin fields to existing Django models as requested in issue #195.

### Key Components Delivered:

‚úÖ **21 Migration Safety Tests** (`core/tests/test_migration_strategy.py`)
- Data preservation across forward/backward migrations  
- Default value application and audit field population
- Data integrity maintenance (FK constraints, unique constraints, cascades)
- Edge case handling (null values, long names, user deletion, timestamps)
- Performance testing with realistic data volumes (up to 100 objects)
- Concurrency testing for post-migration behavior
- Rollback safety and atomicity verification
- Audit trail integration testing

‚úÖ **Data Migration Files** (addresses audit field population)
- `characters/migrations/0004_populate_audit_fields.py` - Uses `player_owner` for audit fields
- `items/migrations/0004_populate_audit_fields.py` - Uses `campaign.owner` for audit fields  
- `locations/migrations/0004_populate_audit_fields.py` - Uses `campaign.owner` for audit fields
- All migrations include proper rollback functionality

‚úÖ **Automated Rollback Script** (`scripts/rollback_mixin_migrations.sh`)
- Interactive safety confirmations
- Step-by-step rollback process (data migrations first, then schema)
- Environment detection and progress reporting
- Complete rollback of both schema (0003) and data (0004) migrations

‚úÖ **Comprehensive Documentation** (`docs/MIGRATION_STRATEGY.md`)
- Pre-migration checklists and safety procedures
- Step-by-step production deployment guidelines
- Post-migration validation procedures
- Performance considerations and monitoring guidance
- Troubleshooting section with common issues and solutions

### Migration Strategy Overview:

**Schema Migrations (0003):**
- Add `created_by`, `modified_by` fields to Character, Item, Location models
- Update timestamp field configurations for proper indexing
- Enhance name field with standardized help text

**Data Migrations (0004):**  
- Populate audit fields with sensible defaults for existing records
- Characters: Use `player_owner` (most logical ownership)
- Items/Locations: Use `campaign.owner` (campaign-level resources)
- Atomic operations with proper error handling

### Testing Results:
- **All 1210 tests passing** ‚úÖ (including the 21 new migration safety tests)
- **Zero regressions** - All existing functionality preserved
- **Migration safety validated** - Data preservation, integrity, and rollback confirmed

### Production Safety Features:
- Comprehensive test coverage ensuring zero data loss
- Multiple rollback options (automated script + manual procedures)
- Performance testing validates migrations complete in reasonable time
- Edge case testing covers real-world scenarios (user deletion, constraints, etc.)

### Documentation Updates:
- Enhanced `docs/development-guide.md` with migration testing procedures
- Updated `docs/database-schema.md` with migration strategy documentation
- Enhanced `docs/deployment.md` with production migration procedures
- Integrated with existing `CLAUDE.md` development workflow

## Test Plan

‚úÖ Migration safety tests (21 tests) - All passing
‚úÖ Full test suite (1210 tests) - All passing  
‚úÖ Data preservation verified
‚úÖ Rollback procedures tested
‚úÖ Documentation comprehensive and validated

Input: gpio-keys - fix a sleep while atomic with PREEMPT_RT

commit f4a8f561d08e39f7833d4a278ebfb12a41eef15f upstream.

When enabling PREEMPT_RT, the gpio_keys_irq_timer() callback runs in
hard irq context, but the input_event() takes a spin_lock, which isn't
allowed there as it is converted to a rt_spin_lock().

[ 4054.289999] BUG: sleeping function called from invalid context at kernel/locking/spinlock_rt.c:48
[ 4054.290028] in_atomic(): 1, irqs_disabled(): 1, non_block: 0, pid: 0, name: swapper/0
...
[ 4054.290195]  __might_resched+0x13c/0x1f4
[ 4054.290209]  rt_spin_lock+0x54/0x11c
[ 4054.290219]  input_event+0x48/0x80
[ 4054.290230]  gpio_keys_irq_timer+0x4c/0x78
[ 4054.290243]  __hrtimer_run_queues+0x1a4/0x438
[ 4054.290257]  hrtimer_interrupt+0xe4/0x240
[ 4054.290269]  arch_timer_handler_phys+0x2c/0x44
[ 4054.290283]  handle_percpu_devid_irq+0x8c/0x14c
[ 4054.290297]  handle_irq_desc+0x40/0x58
[ 4054.290307]  generic_handle_domain_irq+0x1c/0x28
[ 4054.290316]  gic_handle_irq+0x44/0xcc

Considering the gpio_keys_irq_isr() can run in any context, e.g. it can
be threaded, it seems there's no point in requesting the timer isr to
run in hard irq context.

Relax the hrtimer not to use the hard context.

Fixes: 019002f20cb5 ("Input: gpio-keys - use hrtimer for release timer")

regulator: core: fix NULL dereference on unbind due to stale coupling data

[ Upstream commit ca46946a482238b0cdea459fb82fc837fb36260e ]

Failing to reset coupling_desc.n_coupled after freeing coupled_rdevs can
lead to NULL pointer dereference when regulators are accessed post-unbind.

This can happen during runtime PM or other regulator operations that rely
on coupling metadata.

For example, on ridesx4, unbinding the 'reg-dummy' platform device triggers
a panic in regulator_lock_recursive() due to stale coupling state.

Ensure n_coupled is set to 0 to prevent access to invalid pointers.

regmap: fix potential memory leak of regmap_bus

[ Upstream commit c871c199accb39d0f4cb941ad0dccabfc21e9214 ]

When __regmap_init() is called from __regmap_init_i2c() and
__regmap_init_spi() (and their devm versions), the bus argument
obtained from regmap_get_i2c_bus() and regmap_get_spi_bus(), may be
allocated using kmemdup() to support quirks. In those cases, the
bus->free_on_exit field is set to true.

However, inside __regmap_init(), buf is not freed on any error path.
This could lead to a memory leak of regmap_bus when __regmap_init()
fails. Fix that by freeing bus on error path when free_on_exit is set.

Fixes: ea030ca68819 ("regmap-i2c: Set regmap max raw r/w from quirks")

is not held in this context.

mask is guaranteed to be valid in this callback. So, just use

i40e: When removing VF MAC filters, only check PF-set MAC

[ Upstream commit 5a0df02999dbe838c3feed54b1d59e9445f68b89 ]

When the PF is processing an Admin Queue message to delete a VF's MACs
from the MAC filter, we currently check if the PF set the MAC and if
the VF is trusted.

This results in undesirable behaviour, where if a trusted VF with a
PF-set MAC sets itself down (which sends an AQ message to delete the
VF's MAC filters) then the VF MAC is erased from the interface.

This results in the VF losing its PF-set MAC which should not happen.

There is no need to check for trust at all, because an untrusted VF
cannot change its own MAC. The only check needed is whether the PF set
the MAC. If the PF set the MAC, then don't erase the MAC on link-down.

Resolve this by changing the deletion check only for PF-set MAC.

(the out-of-tree driver has also intentionally removed the check for VF
trust here with OOT driver version 2.26.8, this changes the Linux kernel
driver behaviour and comment to match the OOT driver behaviour)
